                <msContents>
                  <summary><title type="uniform" xml:lang="en">Ivar Baardssøn's Description of
                        Greenland</title>. <name type="person" key="IvaBar001">Ivar Baardssøn</name>
                     (Ívar Bárðarson) was a Norwegian who was sent by Bishop <name type="person">Hákon</name> of <name type="place" key="Berge01">Bergen</name> to the (then
                     unoccupied) bishop's seat at <name type="place">Garðar (now
                        Igaliko)</name> in <country key="GR">Greenland</country> in <date when="1341">1341</date> and acted there as <foreign xml:lang="la">officialis</foreign>, steward or superindendent, from <date when="1347">1347</date>. The description of Greenland attributed to him dates from
                     after his return to <country key="NO">Norway</country>, probably in about <date when="1364">1364</date>. The original is lost, but a Danish translation from
                        <date notBefore="1500" notAfter="1599">the 16th century</date> survives in
                     several 17th-century manuscripts, of which this is the best
                     preserved.</summary>
                  <msItem class="landfr">
                     <title type="uniform" xml:lang="en">Ivar Baardssøn's Description of
                        Greenland</title>
